Anonymous Thu 24 Dec 2020 18:11:15 No.34972767 Report
Quoted By: >>34972906
>>34972606
I used to pants everything, but learning to revise yourself is even more important than anything except basic grammar.
One of the reasons I keep multiple projects going is any writer is eventually going to hit that torch it point. But imo that's usually a sign you tried to force your way past issues that should have been acknowledged long ago.
You need to get over that disgust. First drafts are messy. Set it aside, write something else. Come back a week or two later and be clinical about it. No feelings, just take notes. Step back and compare those to your outline.
And don't try to edit every flaw in one pass. I've used anywhere from two to a few dozen, concentrating on small areas each time.
Like an artist working on fundamentals, it sucks and takes time. But the better you get at it, the easier your best first drafts will feel.

Anonymous Thu 24 Dec 2020 18:45:45 No.34973243 Report
Quoted By: >>34973355
>>34972906
You don't. The old phrase write drunk, edit sober exists for a reason. Don't overthink things.
If you believed in the characters and idea to begin with, you're on the right track. In my case almost everything is edit up. I cut when needed, and I've cut big time, but I've usually taken a lot of time after the first draft. My worst story was written/edited in three days, and while I felt perfect then it just didn't flow.

For me at least, I expect characters to react to each other and understand some of their thoughts through dialogue. If I've got that, then I can layer on descriptions and narration.
A reader may not like it, but if I feel the result is too puppety, back to the drawing board. So I feel my best stuff is when the characters forget me. The further I get from a faceless Anon, the better.

On the other hand, I probably should do just the opposite one time. Make him faceless. Leave a few (extremely) subtle hooks. Then challenge the reader to be anything other than an Anon.
